  "prompt": "Can an isosceles triangle be a right triangle? Why or why not?",
  "response": "Yes, an isosceles triangle can be a right triangle. Here's why:\n\nAn **isosceles triangle** is defined as a triangle with at least two sides that are equal in length. A **right triangle** is a triangle that has one angle measuring exactly 90 degrees.\n\nAn **isosceles right triangle** is a special case where:\n1. Two sides are equal in length (the legs), and\n2. One angle is 90 degrees.\n\nIn such a triangle:\n- The two equal sides are the legs of the right triangle.\n- The hypotenuse (the side opposite the right angle) is longer than the legs and is calculated using the Pythagorean theorem: \\( \\text{hypotenuse} = \\sqrt{2} \\times \\text{leg length} \\).\n\nThus, an isosceles triangle can indeed be a right triangle when it satisfies these conditions.",
